===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} – pictographic representation of a [[crescent moon]]. Related to {{l|zh|夕}} and interchangeable in the past, but both are unrelated to [[多]], in which it represents two pieces of meat stylized as [[夕]].

Unrelated to:
* [[前]], in which it represents a boat [[舟]] ([[歬]] > [[𠝣]] > [[𣦃]] > 前);
* [[朕]], in which it represents a boat again ([[𦩎]] > [[𦨶]] > 朕)
* [[青]], in which it represents cinnabar [[丹]] ([[𤯞]] > [[靑]] > 青);
* [[赢]], in which it represents the elongated face of a kind of dragon, perhaps a [[蟠龙|Panlong]];
* [[祭]] and [[將]], in which it represents sacrificed meat stylized as [[𱼀]];
* [[然]], in which it represents dog meat ([[肰]]).
* [[肖]] and [[有]], in which it represents just meat.

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-ŋʷ(j)a-t||moon; star}}, whence also {{w|Magar language|Magar}} {{m|und||tr='''gya''' hot|t=moon}}, {{cog|tbq-lob-pro|*mwatᴸ|t=star; moon}} (whence {{cog|lhu|məʔkə|'''məʔ'''-kə|t=star}}), {{cog|duu|gurmet||star}} ({{zh-ref|Matisoff, 1980}}; {{zh-ref|LaPolla, 1987}}; STEDT).

Various alternative etymologies have also been proposed:
* {{zh-ref|Unger (1992)}} proposes cognation with {{cog|bo|ངོ||tr=ngo|waxing and waning moon; half moon}} (as in {{m|bo|མར་ངོ||tr=mar ngo|waning moon}} and {{m|bo|ཡར་ངོ||tr=yar ngo|waxing moon}}), which {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} connects to {{cog|sit-pro|*s-ŋow||white; light colour}}. However, {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}} points out that the Tibetan word may be analyzed as a derivative of {{cog|bo|ངོ||tr=ngo|face}}, which would mean the semantic connection between “moon” and “face” had to occur either independently in Chinese and Tibetan or in Proto-Sino-Tibetan; it also requires positing a suffix {{m|und|-t}} in Chinese.
* {{zh-ref|Pulleybank (1995a)}} proposes another etymology based on the glyph for {{l|zh|名}} (reconstructed as {{m|und|*màŋʲ}}), which he analyses as a phono-semantic compound of phonetic {{l|zh|夕|t=moon}} and semantic {{l|zh|口|t=mouth}}. He suggests that the phonetic component represents a lost word {{m|und|*màŋʲ||moon}}, and reconstructs {{lang|zh|月}} as {{m|und|*mŋʲ}} (consonantal frame of “moon”) + {{m|und|*-at}} (suffix) > {{m|und|*ŋʲʷat}}. However, there are more straightforward ways of explaining the glyph origin of {{l|zh|名}} (see there), which would nullify the hypothesis of the lost word.
* Related to {{l|zh|越|t=to pass over; to cross over}} in some way.
** {{zh-ref|Mei (1979)}} derives {{lang|zh|月}} from {{och-l|越|tr=**gjot > *gwjat}}: {{m|und|**N-gjot > *ngwjat}}. Also in this proposed word family is {{och-l|歲|tr=**s-gjots > *skwjadh|year}}. The semantics of this word family is centred around "to pass; to elapse". While {{zh-ref|Matisoff (1980)}} seems supportive of this word family, STEDT reconstructs {{cog|tbq-pro|*ɢʷrat|*grwat|to travel; to go through}} for {{l|zh|越}} and {{l|zh|歲}}, separate from the root for {{lang|zh|月}}.
** {{zh-ref|Ferlus (2012)}} reconstructs the {{cog|och|-}} as {{m|und|*ŋ.wat}} and puts it in a word family formed from a Chinese root {{m|und|*wat}}, having a meaning of "circularity" or "circular boundary". This proposed word family includes {{och-l|越|tr=*wat|gloss=to cross over}}, as in "to cross the enclosure of the village", and {{och-l|外|tr=*ŋ.wat-s|gloss=outside}}, as in "out of the enclosure of the village".

